    "answers": [
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/abea6bc1b7772cb2fffe701d4b7be90b?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG&f=y&so-version=2",
                "account_id": 3625253,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 3023077,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/3023077/mark-wagoner",
                "reputation": 1757,
                "display_name": "Mark Wagoner",
                "accept_rate": 50
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 0,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1396526268,
            "creation_date": 1396526268,
            "body": "<p>If all you want to do is split the string after each occurrence of 'NIL' you can use the Java String.Split method.  You don't need a regex.<\/p>\n\n<p>See if this helps: <a href=\"https://stackoverflow.com/questions/3481828/how-to-split-a-string-in-java\">How to split a string in Java<\/a><\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 22836992,
            "question_id": 22836861,
            "last_edit_date": 1495542128
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://i.sstatic.net/LrA7C.jpg?s=256",
                "account_id": 2545685,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 2210548,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/2210548/kraiss",
                "reputation": 999,
                "display_name": "Kraiss",
                "accept_rate": 80
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 0,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1396526294,
            "creation_date": 1396526294,
            "body": "<pre><code>StringTokenizer st = new StringTokenizer(youOriginalString, \" \");\nString theStringYouWant = \"\";\nInteger i = 0;\n\nwhile(st.hasMoreElements()) {\n    theStringYouWant += st.next().toString();\n    i++;\n    if (i % 4 == 0) {\n        theStringYouWant += \"\\n\"; \n    }\n}\n<\/code><\/pre>\n",
            "answer_id": 22837004,
            "question_id": 22836861
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://i.sstatic.net/w7pZ9.jpg?s=256",
                "account_id": 2785888,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 2397315,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/2397315/vmruiz",
                "reputation": 1981,
                "display_name": "VMRuiz",
                "accept_rate": 80
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 0,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1396526458,
            "creation_date": 1396526458,
            "body": "<p>You don't need regex  pattern for that simple string:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>    String s= 1 Agra Achhnera NIL 2 Agra Agra NIL 3 Agra Fatehabad NIL 4 Agra Fatehpur Sikri NIL 5 Agra Jagner NIL 6 Agra Jarar NIL 7 Agra Khairagarh NIL 8 Agra Shamshabad NIL 9 Aligarh Atrauli NIL 10 Aligarh Chharra NIL 11 Aligarh Aligarh 1300.00 12 Aligarh Khair 1300.00 13 Allahabad Allahabad NIL 14 Allahabad Jasra NIL 15 Allahabad Leriyari NIL 16 Allahabad Sirsa NIL 17 Ambedkar Nagar Akbarpur NIL 18 Ambedkar Nagar Tanda Akbarpur NIL  \n    String[] parts = string.split(\" \");\n    for(String string: parts){\n        System.out.print(string); \n        if (string.equals(\"NIL\"))\n            System.out.print(\"\\n\");\n        else \n            System.out.print(\"\\t\");\n}\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>It's not so nice like using a regex pattern but you are gonna have less headaches.<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 22837072,
            "question_id": 22836861
        }
    ],
